.TH "KEYS\-VAULT" "1" "" "keys\-vault" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
keys\-vault \[em] file\-based encryption for sensitive directories via
gocryptfs + GNOME Keyring
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]keys\-vault\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]command\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]keys\-vault\f[R] manages an encrypted gocryptfs volume.
The encrypted ciphertext is stored in a hidden directory; the plaintext
is mounted via FUSE.
The passphrase is stored in GNOME Keyring for automatic unlock.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
\f[B]init\f[R]
Create a new encrypted volume and store the passphrase in GNOME Keyring.
Offers a choice between a randomly generated passphrase and a
user\-supplied one.
Refuses to initialize if the plaintext directory is not empty.
.TP
\f[B]open\f[R]
Mount the vault using the passphrase from GNOME Keyring.
Automatically recovers stale FUSE mounts.
No\-op if already mounted or not initialized.
.TP
\f[B]close\f[R]
Unmount the vault.
Handles stale mounts.
No\-op if not mounted.
.TP
\f[B]status\f[R]
Print the current state: \f[B]open\f[R], \f[B]locked\f[R],
\f[B]stale\f[R], or \f[B]not initialized\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]passwd\f[R]
Rotate the gocryptfs passphrase and update the keyring entry.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-\-dir\f[R]=\f[I]PATH\f[R]
Plaintext mount point.
Default: \f[B]\[ti]/keys\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-\-cipher\-dir\f[R]=\f[I]PATH\f[R]
Encrypted ciphertext directory.
Default: derived from \f[B]\-\-dir\f[R] as a hidden directory with
\f[B].enc\f[R] suffix in the same parent directory (e.g., \[ti]/keys →
\[ti]/.keys.enc, \[ti]/secure/vault → \[ti]/secure/.vault.enc).
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R], \f[B]\-\-help\f[R]
Show usage information.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-version\f[R]
Show version.
.SH CONFIGURATION
Configuration is read from (in order, later values override earlier):
.IP "1." 3
\f[B]/etc/keys\-vault.conf\f[R] \[em] system\-wide defaults
.IP "2." 3
\f[B]$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/keys\-vault.conf\f[R] (default:
\f[B]\[ti]/.config/keys\-vault.conf\f[R]) \[em] per\-user overrides
.PP
CLI flags take precedence over configuration files.
.PP
Configuration files use \f[B]KEY = VALUE\f[R] format.
Only whitelisted keys are accepted; unknown keys produce a warning and
are ignored.
Both
\f[B]\f[BI]H\f[B]\f[BI]O\f[B]\f[BI]M\f[B]\f[BI]E\f[B] * *, **{HOME}\f[R],
and \f[B]\[ti]\f[R] are expanded in paths.
Surrounding quotes (single or double) are stripped from values.
Inline comments (after space\-hash) are stripped.
.SS Variables
.TP
\f[B]PLAIN_DIR\f[R]
Plaintext mount point.
Default: \f[B]$HOME/keys\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]CIPHER_DIR\f[R]
Encrypted ciphertext directory.
Default: derived from PLAIN_DIR.
.SH STALE MOUNT RECOVERY
If the gocryptfs process dies (e.g., OOM kill) the FUSE mountpoint
becomes stale \[em] it appears in \f[I]/proc/mounts\f[R] but
\f[I]stat\f[R](2) fails with \[lq]Transport endpoint is not
connected\[rq].
.PP
\f[B]open\f[R] detects this and force\-unmounts the stale mountpoint
before re\-mounting.
\f[B]close\f[R] also handles stale mounts.
\f[B]status\f[R] reports \f[B]stale\f[R] as a distinct state.
.SH KEYRING
Passphrases are stored in GNOME Keyring via \f[B]secret\-tool\f[R](1).
Each vault directory gets a unique keyring entry keyed by its resolved
plaintext path.
.SH EXAMPLES
Initialize and open a vault at the default location:
.IP
.EX
keys\-vault init
keys\-vault open
.EE
.PP
Use a custom directory:
.IP
.EX
keys\-vault \-\-dir=\[ti]/secure/credentials init
keys\-vault \-\-dir=\[ti]/secure/credentials open
.EE
.PP
Or configure via file:
.IP
.EX
echo \[aq]PLAIN_DIR = $HOME/secure/credentials\[aq] > \[ti]/.config/keys\-vault.conf
keys\-vault init
.EE
.PP
Check status:
.IP
.EX
keys\-vault status
.EE
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[I]/etc/keys\-vault.conf\f[R]
System\-wide configuration.
.TP
\f[I]\[ti]/.config/keys\-vault.conf\f[R]
Per\-user configuration.
.SH SEE ALSO
\f[B]gocryptfs\f[R](1), \f[B]secret\-tool\f[R](1),
